      "value": "Warner Unified is a small, rural K-12 district in the North Inland region of San Diego County. About 413 of its students have an IEP, and 70 of them \u2014 roughly 17% \u2014 have an autism (ASD) eligibility. Around 76% of those autistic students spend most of the school day in a general-education classroom."
    },
    "what_this_means_for_parents": {
      "ai_disclaimer": "This summary was written by an AI model from the data points in this profile. The underlying numbers come from public California government sources, but the narrative is AI-written and may contain inaccuracies. Verify specific claims directly with the school district before making decisions.",
      "ai_generated": true,
      "ai_generated_at": "2026-05-18T05:52:05Z",
      "ai_model": "claude-opus (via Claude Code session)",
      "based_on_sources": [
        "cde_spedps",
        "ca_dashboard",
        "ocr",
        "oah"
      ],
      "value": "About 76% of autistic students here are in a general-education classroom for most of the day, and none are reported in a fully separate setting. Among all students with disabilities, a broader group than autism alone, 88% are in general-education classrooms most of the day. On 2024-25 state tests, students with disabilities scored about 124 points below standard in English and 153 below in math, while students overall were 58 and 93 points below. Students with disabilities were chronically absent at about 7%, close to the 5% rate for all students, and were suspended at about 8% (compared with 4%)."
    }
  },
